    <h3>Implementation:</h3>
    <p>The implementation is fairly straight forward.</p>
    <b>Step 1:</b>
    <p>Set <code>data-route</code> attribute to button link and collapse section.</p>
    <p>We will use <code>data-route</code> to trigger route, as well as to filter sections for activation.</p>
    <p>We will also use <code>hash</code> routing this time to demonstrate how hash routing works. We will set hash route as follows:</p>
    <pre>
        <code>
    &lt;button ... data-route="<b>#/accordion1</b>"&gt;...&lt;/button&gt;</code>
    </pre>
    <p>For the three buttons above we will set routes as <code>#/accordion1</code>, <code>#/accordion2</code>, and <code>#/accordion3</code>.</p>
    <b>Step 2:</b>
    <p>Bind click event to button link.</p>
    <pre>
        <code>
    $('.btn-link').on('click', function (e) {
        if ($(this).attr('aria-expanded') === 'true') {
            e.stopPropagation(); <span class="comment">// To register true accordion functionality</span>
        } else {
            $.router.set($(this).data('route'), <b>false, true</b>);
        }
    });</code>
    </pre>
    <p>Notice the last two parameters in <code>router.set</code> method. The second last parameter is set to <code>false</code> so that we can register new history entries. The last parameter is set to <code>true</code> in order to prevent calling route handler. We want to let bootstrap handle the expand/collapse functionality of accordion.</p>
    <b>Step 3:</b>
    <p>Handle routing when user refreshes the page. Since the route is triggered by browser itself, the handler will be called anyway.</p>
    <pre>
        <code>
    $.route(function (data) {
        if (<b>/accordion/</b>.test(data.route) && data.hash) {
            $('.btn-link')
                .attr('aria-expanded', false)
                .filter(`[data-route="${<b>data.route</b>}"]`)
                .attr('aria-expanded', true);
            $('.collapse')
                .removeClass('show')
                .filter(`[data-route="${<b>data.route</b>}"]`)
                .addClass('show');
        }
    });</code>
    </pre>
    <p>We have registered a generic route because it makes it easier to handle multiple urls in a single handler. A generic route listens to all kinds of route changes.</p>
    <p>A specific route is registered by passing a route string parameter: <code>$.route('&lt;route&gt;', handler);</code></p>
    <p>However, in cases where there are too many routes, registering individual handlers invite lots of issues especially related to performance.</p>
